<div1 type="letter">

<pb facs="nei.j4c.65.31" />

<fw type="curatorial">31</fw>

<opener>
<dateline>
5835 Vine Street<lb/>
Lincoln, Nebraska 68505<lb/>
May 24, 1973
</dateline>

<address>
<addrLine>Mr. George Babcock</addrLine>
<addrLine>2503 Brookside Avenue</addrLine>
<addrLine>Omaha, Nebraska 68124</addrLine>
</address>

<salute>Dear George:</salute>
</opener>
<p>Thanks for a good letter, and for your kind words about me and my poetry.</p>

<p>You say that you also try to write poetry but have difficulty in getting it "off the ground." Judging by the verses you sent me, I would not be surprised that sometime in the future, if you work hard, you may be able to get one foot off the ground, if not both.</p>

<p>Meanwhile, read English poets, and I think it would be good for you to become acquainted with my lyric entitled "Poet's Advice." You will find it on page 110 in my <hi rend="caps">LYRIC AND DRAMATIC POEMS</hi>. It was written to a boy of about your age whose name was also George.</p>
<closer>
<salute>With every good wish, your friend,</salute>


<signed>John G. Neihardt</signed>

<note>JGN:nh</note>
</closer>

</div1>
</body>

